<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Ora is intentionally NOT sandboxed.

  The dictation pipeline injects text into the frontmost foreign app
  by posting a synthetic Cmd+V via CGEvent.post(tap: .cghidEventTap).
  macOS forbids sandboxed apps from posting cross-app events AND
  refuses to grant Accessibility access to sandboxed apps in the
  first place — TCC will not even add a sandboxed app to the
  System Settings ▸ Privacy & Security ▸ Accessibility list,
  because the entitlement that backs that grant is blocked by the
  sandbox itself. Whisper (the predecessor) ships with the sandbox
  off for the same reason.

  Trade-off: we lose the sandbox's filesystem isolation and
  defense-in-depth. There is no workaround on macOS — every
  dictation tool with cross-app text injection takes this trade.

  Mic access still works inside or outside the sandbox via the
  com.apple.security.device.audio-input entitlement, which TCC
  treats independently.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
	<false/>
	<key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
